A058001.name: Number of 3 X 3 matrices with entries mod n, up to row and column permutation.

A058002.name: Number of 4 X 4 matrices with entries mod n, up to row and column permutation.

A058003.name: Number of 5 X 5 matrices with entries mod n, up to row and column permutation.

A058004.name: Number of 6 X 6 matrices with entries mod n, up to row and column permutation.

A058006.name: Alternating factorials: 0! - 1! + 2! - ... + (-1)^n n!
formula: G.f.: G(0)/(1-x), where G(k)= 1 - (2*k + 1)*x/( 1 - 2*x*(k+1)/(2*x*(k+1) - 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 24 2013
a(n) = exp(1)*Gamma(0,1) + (-1)^n*exp(1)*(n+1)!*Gamma(-n-1,1), where Gamma(a,x) is the upper incomplete Gamma function. - _Vladimir Reshetnikov_, Oct 29 2015

A058007.name: Freestyle perfect numbers n = Product_{i=1,..,k} f_i^e_i where 1 < f_1 <  ... < f_k, e_i > 0, such that 2n = Product_{i=1,..,k} (f_i^(e_i+1)-1)/(f_i-1).

A058008.name: Numbers k such that (2*k - 1)!/(k!)^2 is an integer.
formula: Appears to be A067348(n)/2. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Mar 21 2003
Terms >1 are given by A002503+1. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Dec 09 2017

A058009.name: a(n) is obtained by applying the map k -> prime(k) n times, starting at n.

A058010.name: The main diagonal of N. Fernandez's Order of Primeness array.

A058011.name: Consider the sequence {b(m)} of nonprimes; sequence gives values of m where gcd{m, b(m)} increases.

A058012.name: Consider the sequence {b(m)} of composite numbers (excluding 1); sequence gives values of m where gcd(m, b(m)) increases.

A058013.name: Smallest prime p such that (n+1)^p - n^p is prime.
formula: a((p-1)/2) = 2 for odd primes p. - _Alexander Adamchuk_, Dec 01 2006

A058014.name: Number of labeled trees with n+1 nodes such that the degrees of all nodes, excluding the first node, are odd.
formula: E.g.f. A(x) equals the inverse function of 2*x*log(x)/(1 + x^2).
E.g.f. A(x)=exp(B(x)), B(x) satisfies B(x)=x*cosh(B(x)). [_Vladimir Kruchinin_, Apr 19 2011]

A058015.name: Numbers k such that 2^k + k^3 is prime.

A058016.name: Digits of the zero of the 37-adic L-function with cyclotomic character of index 31.

A058017.name: Smallest prime >= LCM(1,...,x), where x is a prime power.

A058018.name: Difference between LCM(1,...,x) and first prime >= LCM(1,...,x), where x is a prime power.

A058020.name: Difference between lcm(1,..,n) and the smallest prime > lcm(1,...,n) + 1, where n runs over A000961, lcm(n) runs through A051451.

A058021.name: Largest prime preceding distinct values of lcm(1,...,m): Max{p|p < A003418(A000961(n))}. To get different LCM values, the last arguments(m) of LCM were selected from A000961.

A058022.name: Difference between lcm(1,..,n) and the largest prime before lcm(1,..,n) where n runs over the prime powers A000961, LCMs are in A051451.

A058023.name: Largest prime < LCM{1,...,x} - 1: values of x were taken from A000961 so as to generate the values of the LCM exactly once.

A058024.name: Difference between lcm(1,...,x)-1 and largest preceding prime. Numbers of x for LCM were taken of A000961 to obtain distinct LCM values exactly once.

A058025.name: Numbers k such that 3*13^k - 2 is prime.

A058026.name: Number of positive integers, k, where k <= n and gcd(k,n) = gcd(k+1,n) = 1.
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = p^(e-1)*(p-2). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Dec 01 2001
a(n) = Sum_{d divides n} phi(n/d)*(-1)^omega(d). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Sep 26 2002
a(n) = n*Product_{primes p|n} (1-2/p). Dirichlet g.f. zeta(s-1)*product_p (1-2*p^(-s)). - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 15 2011
a(n) = phi(n) * Sum_{d|n} mu(d)/phi(d), where mu(k) is the Moebius function and phi(k) is the Euler totient function. - _Daniel Suteu_, Jun 23 2018

A058027.name: Sum of terms of continued fraction for n-th harmonic number, 1 + 1/2 + 1/3 + ... + 1/n.

A058028.name: Sum of the terms of the continued fraction for the sum of the reciprocals of the first n primes.

A058029.name: Primes closest to LCM[1,...,x] either above or below. Arguments x were selected from A000961 (powers of primes including primes) in order to obtain distinct values of LCM exactly once.

A058030.name: Signed distance of primes from LCM[1,...,x] being closest to it. Arguments x were selected from A000961 (powers of primes including primes) in order to use distinct values of LCM exactly once. When both closest primes are in the same distance, then negative were used.

A058031.name: a(n) = n^4 - 2*n^3 + 3*n^2 - 2*n + 1, the Alexander polynomial for reef and granny knots.
formula: a(n) = (n*(n-1))^2 + (n-1)^2 + n^2, sum of three squares. - _Carmine Suriano_, Jun 16 2014
For n>0  a(n) = A002522(n)*A002522(n-1) - 1. - _Bruce J. Nicholson_, Jul 02 2017

A058033.name: Number of powers of 2 between (but not including) two consecutive primorials.

A058034.name: Number of numbers whose cube root rounds to n.

A058035.name: Largest 4th-power-free number dividing n.
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = p ^ min(e,3), p prime, e > 0. [_Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jan 06 2012]

A058036.name: Smallest primitive prime factor of the n-th Lucas number (A000032); i.e., L(n), L(0) = 2, L(1) = 1 and L(n) = L(n-1) + L(n-2).

A058037.name: Numbers n such that 3^n - n is prime.

A058038.name: a(n) = Fibonacci(2*n)*Fibonacci(2*n+2).
formula: a(n) is the next integer from ((3+sqrt(5))*((7+3*sqrt(5))/2)^(n-1)-6)/10. - _Paul Weisenhorn_, May 17 2009
a(n) = (Lucas(4n+2)-3)/5, where Lucas(n)= A000032(n). - _Gary Detlefs_, Dec 07 2010

A058040.name: (p_1,p_2,...,p_m) = prime factors of n; (m>1,k>0); n such that n = Sum_{i=1,2,..,m} k^(p_i).

A058041.name: Noncubes equal to the sum of cubes of their prime factors.

A058042.name: Trajectory of binary number 10110 under the operation 'Reverse and Add!' carried out in base 2.

A058044.name: Difference between the smallest prime following and largest prime preceding n-th primorial number.

A058045.name: Numbers k such that (5^k + k)/3 is prime.

A058046.name: Numbers n such that 5^n - n is prime.

A058047.name: Generalized Collatz sequences: primes resulting in a cycle containing 1.

A058048.name: For each prime P consider the generalized Collatz sequence of each integer N > 1 defined by c(0) = N, c(m+1) = c(m) * P + 1 if F > P, else c(m+1) = c(m) / F, where F is the smallest factor of c(m), until the sequence cycles. If all c(i) > 1 for some starting number N then P belongs to the sequence (and vice versa).

A058049.name: Numbers n such that the sum of the digits of the n first primes is a prime.

A058050.name: a(n) is the number of different graphs drawn in the following way: you decide for each number k <= n on a pair of positive numbers (x(k),y(k)) such that x(k)+y(k)=k; you draw n points numbered 1 to n; draw two arrows from n, one to x(n) and one to y(n); draw two arrows from each k already reached by an arrow, one to x(k) and one to y(k). The process stops when 1 is the only point reached by an arrow without any arrow leaving it; you can also erase the isolated points.

A058051.name: a(n) = F(F(F(n))), where F is a Fibonacci number (A000045).

A058052.name: Sum of the distances between the 2^n vertices in the De Bruijn Graphs on words of length n on alphabet {0,1}.

A058053.name: Number of 3-rowed binary matrices with n ones and no zero columns, up to row and column permutation.

A058054.name: Smallest prime > n! minus largest prime <= n!.

A058055.name: a(n) is the smallest positive number m such that m^2 + n is the next prime > m^2.
formula: a(n) = Min{ m > 0 | m^2 + n is the next prime after m^2}.

A058056.name: a(n) = p is the smallest prime such that p = n + h(n)^2 and p is the first prime following h(n)^2. The smallest immediate post-square primes with distance n = p - h(n)^2.

A058057.name: Triangle giving coefficients of ménage hit polynomials.

A058059.name: Numbers n such that x^n + x + 2 is irreducible over GF(3).

A058060.name: Number of distinct prime factors of d(n), the number of divisors of n.

A058061.name: Number of prime factors (counted with multiplicity) of d(n), the number of divisors of n.

A058062.name: Number of distinct prime factors of sigma(n), the sum of the divisors of n.

A058063.name: Number of prime factors (when counted with multiplicity) of sigma(n), the sum of divisors of n.

A058064.name: Find least k such that (n+1)^k + n^k is a prime (A057856); then k=2^m and sequence gives values of m.

A058065.name: Complement of A057843.
formula: a(n) = floor(tau*n+sqrt(5))-2 where tau is the Golden ratio = (1+sqrt(5))/2. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Apr 14 2003

A058067.name: Number of polynomial functions from Z to Z/nZ.
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = p^t_p(e). - _David W. Wilson_, Aug 14 2005 [t_p(e) = Sum_{k>=0: e > A090622(k, p)} (e - A090622(k, p)) = p * Sum_{k = 1..e} max(0, k - A090622(e-k, p)). In particular, t_p(e) = p*e*(e+1)/2 for e <= p. - _Andrey Zabolotskiy_, Nov 09 2017 and Sep 29 2020]
a(prime(n)) = A051674(n). - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 01 2014 [Edited by _Andrey Zabolotskiy_, Nov 08 2017]

A058068.name: Denominators of convergents to Champernowne constant (A033307).

A058069.name: Numerators of convergents to Champernowne constant (A033307).

A058071.name: A Fibonacci triangle: triangle T(n,k) in which n-th row consists of the numbers F(k)F(n+2-k), where F() are the Fibonacci numbers, for n >= 0, 0 <= k <= n+1.
formula: Column k is the (generalized) Fibonacci sequence having first two terms F(k+1), F(k+1). - _Clark Kimberling_, Dec 21 2015

A058072.name: Numbers k such that sigma(k) divides sigma(k+1), where sigma(k) is sum of positive divisors of k.

A058073.name: Numbers k such that sigma(k+1) divides sigma(k), where sigma(k) is the sum of positive divisors of k.

A058074.name: Integers m such that gcd(d(m),d(m+1)) = 1, where d(m) is number of positive divisors of m.

A058075.name: Numbers k such that gcd(sigma(k), sigma(k+1)) = 1, where sigma(k) is sum of positive divisors of k.

A058076.name: Numbers n such that n | sigma_3(n) + sigma_2(n) + sigma_1(n) + sigma_0(n).

A058077.name: Binomial coefficients formed from consecutive primes: a(n) = binomial( prime(n+1), prime(n) ).

A058078.name: Greatest common divisor of two binomial coefficients formed from consecutive primes: a(n) = gcd(C(prime(n+2), prime(n+1)), C(prime(n+1), prime(n))).
formula: a(n) = gcd(f(n+1), f(n)) where f(n) = binomial(prime(n+1), prime(n)). - _Joerg Arndt_, Apr 05 2014

A058079.name: a(n) = p3, where {p1,p2,p3} are 3 consecutive primes with increasing order such that gcd(C(p3,p2), C(p2,p1)) = 1, where C is the binomial coefficient.

A058080.name: Numbers n such that product of divisors of n is > n^2.
formula: Numbers with five or more divisors. - _Lekraj Beedassy_, Sep 11 2003

A058081.name: a(1) = 1; a(n+1) = sum of terms in continued fraction for the sum of the continued fractions, [a(1); a(2), a(3),...,a(n-1),a(n)] and [a(n); a(n-1), a(n-2),...,a(2), a(1)].

A058082.name: a(1) = 1; a(n+1) = sum of terms in continued fraction for the sum of the continued fractions, [a(1); a(2), a(3), ..., a(n)] and [0; a(1), a(2), a(3), ..., a(n)].

A058083.name: a(1) = 1; a(n+1) = sum of terms in continued fraction for sum of continued fractions, [a(n); a(n-1), a(n-2),...,a(1)] and [0; a(n), a(n-1), a(n-2),...,a(1)].

A058084.name: Smallest m such that binomial(m,k) = n for some k.

A058087.name: Triangle read by rows, giving coefficients of the ménage hit polynomials ordered by descending powers. T(n, k) for 0 <= k <= n.
formula: Row n of the triangle lists the coefficients of the polynomial U_n(t) = Sum_{k=0..n} ((2*n/(2*n-k))*binomial(2*n-k,k)*(n-k)!*(t-1)^k, with higher order terms first (Kaplansky and Riordan). - _William P. Orrick_, Aug 09 2020
T(n, k) = Sum_{j=0..k} (-1)^j*(2*n*(k-j)!/(n+k-j))*binomial(n-k+j, n-k)*binomial(n+k-j, n+k+j), with T(0, k) = 1. - _G. C. Greubel_, May 15 2021

A058088.name: McKay-Thompson series of class 8b for Monster.
formula: Expansion of q^(1/2)*(eta(q^2)^4*eta(q^4)^4 / (eta(q)^4*eta(q^8)^4) + 4*eta(q)^4*eta(q^8)^4 / (eta(q^2)^4*eta(q^4)^4)) in powers of q. - _G. A. Edgar_, Mar 23 2017

A058091.name: McKay-Thompson series of class 9B for the Monster group.
formula: Expansion of 3 * q^(1/3) * a(q) / c(q) in powers of q where a(), c() are cubic AGM theta functions. - _Michael Somos_, Aug 09 2006
Given g.f. A(x), then B(q) = A(q^3) / q satisfies 0 = f(B(q), B(q^2)) where f(u, v) = u^3 + v^3 - u^2*v^2 + 9*u*v - 54. - _Michael Somos_, Aug 09 2006
Given g.f. A(x), then B(q) = A(q^3) / q satisfies 0 = f(B(q), B(q^2)) where f(u, v) = (u^3 + 1) * (v^3 + 1) - (u*v + 5) * (u^2*v^2 - 4*u*v + 11). - _Michael Somos_, Aug 20 2014
G.f.: Sum_{k>=0} a(k) * x^(3*k) = 3*x + (Product_{k>0} (1 - x^k) / (1 - x^(9*k)))^3. - _Michael Somos_, Aug 09 2006

A058092.name: McKay-Thompson series of class 9a for the Monster group.
formula: Expansion of (27 * x * (b(x)^3 + c(x)^3)^2 / (b(x) * c(x))^3)^(1/3) in powers of x where b(), c() are cubic AGM theta functions, _Michael Somos_, Jun 16 2012

A058094.name: Number of 321-hexagon-avoiding permutations in S_n, i.e., permutations of 1..n with no submatrix equivalent to 321, 56781234, 46781235, 56718234 or 46718235.

A058095.name: McKay-Thompson series of class 9c for the Monster group.
formula: Expansion of q^(1/3) * 3 * b(q) / c(q) in powers of q where b(), c() are cubic AGM theta functions.
Expansion of q^(1/3) * (eta(q) / eta(q^3))^4 in powers of q. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 24 2007
Given g.f. A(x), then B(q) = A(q^3) / q satisfies 0 = f(B(q), B(q^2)) where f(u, v) = (u+v)^3 - u*v * (u+3) * (v+3) .
Given g.f. A(x), then B(q) = A(q^3) / q satisfies 0 = f(B(q), B(q^2), B(q^4)) where f(u, v, w) = u^2*v^2 + v^2*w^2 - v*u^2*w^2 + u*w*v^2 - 9*u*w * (u+w).
Euler transform of period 3 sequence [ -4, -4, 0, ...]. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 24 2007
a(n) = A112146(3*n - 1). Convolution inverse of A128758.

A058096.name: McKay-Thompson series of class 9d for Monster.
formula: G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (81 t)) = f(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t). - _Michael Somos_, Aug 28 2015
Expansion of A - 3/A, where A = (eta(q^9)^2/(eta(q^3)*eta(q^27)))^2, in powers of q. - _G. C. Greubel_, Jun 03 2018

A058097.name: McKay-Thompson series of class 10A for Monster.
formula: Expansion of A - 6 + 1/A, where A = (eta(q^2)*eta(q^5)/(eta(q)*eta(q^10) ))^6, in powers of q. - _G. C. Greubel_, Jun 13 2018

A058098.name: McKay-Thompson series of class 10B for the Monster group with a(0) = 0.
formula: Expansion of q^-1 * (chi(-q) * chi(-q^5))^4 + 4 in powers of q where chi() is a Ramanujan theta function.
Expansion of (eta(q) * eta(q^5) / (eta(q^2) * eta(q^10)))^4 + 4 in powers of q.
a(n) = A132040(n) unless n = 0. a(n) = -(-1)^n * A112158(n). - _Michael Somos_, Feb 02 2012

A058099.name: McKay-Thompson series of class 10C for Monster.
formula: Expansion of 2 + (eta(q)*eta(q^2)/(eta(q^5)*eta(q^10)))^2 in powers of q. - _G. C. Greubel_, May 05 2018

A058100.name: McKay-Thompson series of class 10D for the Monster group.
formula: G.f. is Fourier series of a weight 0 level 10 modular form. f(-1/ ( 10 t)) = f(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t).
Expansion of -6 + ((eta(q^2)*eta(q^5))/(eta(q)*eta(q^10)))^6 in powers of q. - _G. C. Greubel_, May 05 2018

A058101.name: McKay-Thompson series of class 10E for Monster.

A058102.name: McKay-Thompson series of class 10a for Monster.

A058103.name: McKay-Thompson series of class 10b for Monster.
formula: The g.f. T10b satisfies the quintic equation P5(T10b(q)) = T2A(q^5), where we used T2A from A101558 and polynomial P5(t) = t^5-10*t^3+20*t^2-15*t-100. - _G. A. Edgar_, Apr 03 2017

formula: E.g.f.: 1/(1 + LambertW(-x)) - x*(x + 1)*exp(x), where LambertW() is the Lambert W-function. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Feb 08 2017

A058127.name: Triangle read by rows: T(j,k) = number of acyclic functions from {1,...,j} to {1,...,k}. For n >= 1, a(n) = (k-j)*k^(j-1), where k is such that C(k,2) < n <= C(k+1,2) and j = (n-1) mod C(k,2). Alternatively, table T(k,j) read by antidiagonals with k >= 1, 0 <= j <= k: T(k,j) = number of acyclic-function digraphs on k vertices with j vertices of outdegree 1 and (k-j) vertices of outdegree 0; T(k,j) = (k-j)*k^(j-1).
formula: For fixed m = k-j, a(n) = T(k, j) = T(m+j, j) = m*(m+j)^(j-1). Exponential generating function g for T(m+j, j) = m*(m+j)^(j-1) is given by g(t) = exp(-m*W(-t)), where W denotes the principal branch of Lambert's W function. Lambert's W function satisfies W(t)*exp(W(t)) = t for t >= -exp(-1).
T(n, k) = Sum_{i=0..k} T(n-1, i) * binomial(k, i) if k < n. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 20 2017

a(n) = Sum_{k = 0..floor(n/2)} (-1)^k*(n-2*k)!*binomial(n-k,k)*binomial(n-k+2,k+2). Cf. A058798. - _Peter Bala_, Aug 01 2013

A058807.name: a(n) = Product_{k=1..n} s(n,k), where s(n,k) is unsigned Stirling number of the first kind. (s(n,k) = number of permutations of n elements which contain exactly k cycles.)

A058808.name: Product{k=1 to n}[S(n,k)], where S(n,k) is a Stirling number of the second kind. (S(n,k) = number of ways of partitioning a set of n elements into k nonempty subsets.)

A058809.name: The sequence lambda(3,n), where lambda is defined in A055203. Number of ways of placing n identifiable positive intervals with a total of exactly three starting and/or finishing points.

A058810.name: The sequence lambda(n,n), where lambda is defined in A055203.

A058811.name: Number of terms on the n-th level of the Inverse-Totient-Tree (ITT). The 0th, 1st, 2nd and 3rd levels are {1}, {2}, {3, 4, 6}, {5, 7, 8, 9, 10, 12, 14, 18} with 1, 1, 3, 8 entries resp. The (n+1)-st level is obtained from the n-th level as the union of the inverse phi sets of the terms occurring earlier on the n-th level.
formula: a(n) = Cardinality[Floor(n)], where Floor(0)={1}, Floor(n+1)=Union[invphi(t(i, n)), i=1..a(n))], where t(i, n) is the i-th integer in Floor(n), ordered by size or lexicographically.

A058812.name: Irregular triangle of rows of numbers in increasing order. Row 1 = {1}. Row m + 1 contains all numbers k such that phi(k) is in row m.

A058813.name: Unlabeled (i.e., equivalent to their 1-0 complement) binary necklaces sorted in ascending lexicographic order and read as binary numbers.

formula: Let x(1)=1, x(n+1) = (3/2)*x(n) - floor((3/2)*x(n)); then a(n) = x(n)*2^n - _Benoit Cloitre_, Aug 27 2002

A058843.name: Triangle T(n,k) = C_n(k) where C_n(k) = number of k-colored labeled graphs with n nodes (n >= 1, 1<=k<=n).

The row polynomials R(n,x) satisfy the recurrence equation R(n,x) = x*(1 + sum {k = 0..n-1} binomial(n-1,k)*2^(k*(n-k))*R(k,x)) with R(1,x) = x. The row polynomials appear to have only real zeros.

formula: From the relation G(x)=exp(g(x)) between generating functions for connected g(x) and all G(x) labeled structures and considering generating functions for chordal graphs (c_n, A007134), we have a(n) = c(n) + 1/n * Sum_{k=1}^(n - 1) k * binomial(n, k) * c(k) * a(n - k). [Formula edited by _Michael De Vlieger_, Jul 04 2018]

A058863.name: Number of connected labeled chordal graphs on n nodes with no induced path P_4; also the number of labeled trees with each vertex replaced by a clique.
formula: where c(n) (A058863) is the number of connected graphs of this type and t(n) (A058864) is the total number of such graphs.
a(n) is asymptotic to sqrt(r*(e-1))/n*(n/(e*r))^n where r = 1 - log(e-1).
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} Stirling2(n, k)*A060356(k). Also a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} (-1)^(n-k)*Stirling2(n, k)*k^(k-1). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Sep 17 2003

A058864.name: Number of labeled chordal graphs (connected or not) on n nodes with no induced path P_4.

O.g.f.: Sum_{n>=1} (n+1)^(n-1) * x^n / Product_{k=1..n} (1+k*x). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jul 20 2011
a(n) ~ sqrt(exp(1)-1) * exp(1-n) * n^(n-1) * (1-log(exp(1)-1))^(1/2-n). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Oct 18 2013

a(n,q) = Sum_{k=1..n-2}binomial(n,k)*(A(n-k, q - k(k-1)/2 - k(n-k)) - a(n-k, q - k(k-1)/2 - k(n-k)));

formula: Harary and Prins (following Robinson) give a recurrence.

formula: a(n+1) = (n+1)*2^n - n - 1 = Sum_{j=0..n} (n+j)*2^(n-j-1) = A048493(n)-1 = Column sum of A062111. - _Henry Bottomley_, May 30 2001
a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n-1} binomial(n, k) * (n-k). - _Michael Somos_, Mar 29 2012

A058878.name: Triangle T(n,k) is the number of labeled graphs of even degree with n nodes and k edges (n >= 0, 0 <= k <= n(n-1)/2).
formula: T(n,k) = (1/2^n) * Sum_{s=0..n} binomial(n,s) * Sum_{t=0..k} (-1)^t * binomial(s*(n-s), t) * binomial(binomial(s,2) + binomial(n-s, 2), k-t) for n >= 0 and 0 <= k <= n*(n-1)/2.
T(n, n*(n-1)/2) = 1 if n is odd.
T(n, k) = 0 if n is even and n*(n-1)/2 - n/2 + 1 <= k < n*(n-1)/2.
T(n, n*(n-1)/2 - k) = T(n,k) for 0 <= k <= n*(n-1)/2 if n is odd. (End)

A058879.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = number of connected graphs with one cycle of length m = n - k + 1 and n nodes (n >= 3 and 1 <= k <= n - 2).

formula: a(n) = (1/(2n)) * Sum_{d|n} phi(d) * 2^(2n/d) + (2^((n-4)/2), if n is even). - _Amiram Eldar_, Aug 28 2019

A058889.name: Arrange binary trees in natural sequential order (see examples); sequence gives numbers of nodes.

A058890.name: Smallest number of nodes in a graph whose automorphism group is cyclic of order n.
formula: a(2) = 2; for r > 1, a(2^r) = 2^r + 6; for p = 3 or 5 and r > 0, a(p^r) = p^r + 2p; for p prime >= 7 and r > 0, a(p^r) = p^r + p. (Harary)

a(n) = a(p1^r1 p2^r2 ... pk^rk) = a(p1^r1) + ... + a(pn^rn) - F where F is a "correction factor" which depends on the exponents of the primes 2, 3 and 5 in the prime factorization of the number n. Call these values n2, n3 and n5 respectively.

The correction factor F is 0 if n3 = 0 (so unless 3 divides n, the upper bound is exact); 4 if n2 = 2, n3 >= 1 and n5 = 1; 3 if n2 != 2, n3 >=1 and n5 = 1; 1 if n2 = 2, n3 >= 1 and n5 != 1; 1 if n2 >= 2, n3 = 1 and n5 != 1; 0 otherwise.

A058891.name: a(n) = 2^(2^(n-1) - 1).
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n-1)^2 is an example with a(1) = 1 and k = 2 of a(n) = k*a(n-1)^2; general explicit formula: a(n) = ((a(1)*k)^(2^(n-1)))/k. - Andreas Pfaffel (andreas.pfaffel(AT)gmx.at), Apr 27 2010

A058892.name: E.g.f.: exp(f(x)-1), where f(x) = o.g.f. for partitions (A000041), Product_{k>=1} 1/(1-x^k).

A058963.name: Modular form of Level 4 and weight 5/2.

A058964.name: Decimal expansion of series-parallel constant.
formula: This number, c, is defined by Product_{n=1..inf} (1-c^n)^(-A000669[n]) = 2.

A058965.name: Continued fraction expansion of series-parallel constant.
formula: This number, c, is defined by Product_{n=1..inf} (1-c^n)^(-A000669[n]) = 2.

A058969.name: Numerators of expansion of a function eta(x) related to Cremer points.
formula: eta(x) is the limit of the sequence defined by eta_0 = -x/2; eta_{i+1} = eta_i + x^{i-1} eta_i^2.

A058970.name: Denominators of expansion of a function eta(x) related to Cremer points.
formula: eta(x) is the limit of the sequence defined by eta_0 = -x/2; eta_{i+1} = eta_i + x^{i-1} eta_i^2.

A058971.name: For a rational number p/q let f(p/q) = sum of divisors of p+q divided by number of divisors of p+q; a(n) is obtained by iterating f, starting at n/1, until an integer is reached, or if no integer is ever reached then a(n) = 0.

A058972.name: For a rational number p/q let f(p/q) = sum of aliquot divisors of p+q divided by number of divisors of p+q; sequence gives numbers n such that, starting at n/1 and iterating f, an integer is eventually reached.

A058974.name: a(n) = 0 if n = 1 or a prime, otherwise a(n) = s + a(s) iterated until no change occurs, where s (A008472) is sum of distinct primes dividing n.

A058975.name: Total number of flats in the lattice of contractions of the n-cube. Also number of partitions of vertex set of n-cube into blocks all of which induce connected subgraphs.

A058976.name: Number of inequivalent n-variable 3-valued Post functions under action of complementing group D(n,3).

A058977.name: For a rational number p/q let f(p/q) = sum of distinct prime factors (A008472) of p+q divided by number of distinct prime factors (A001221) of p+q; a(n) is obtained by iterating f, starting at n/1, until an integer is reached, or if no integer is ever reached then a(n) = 0.

A058978.name: Minimal number of (non-consecutive) Fibonacci numbers needed to get n by addition and subtraction.

A058979.name: Number of m such that phi(m) = 4n.

A058980.name: Positive numbers of form 4k such that card(invphi(4*k)=0) (the nontotients congruent to 0 modulo 4).

A058981.name: Improperly Reduced Fibonacci Sequence: begin with a(0) = 0, a(1) = 1 and a(n) = [ a(n-1) + a(n-2) ] / a(k). a(k) is the first (not necessarily the greatest) term including 1 which divides a(n-1) + a(n-2) not previously used.

A058982.name: Increasing values of the Improperly Reduced Fibonacci Sequence (A058981).

A058983.name: Position at which increasing values of the Improperly Reduced Fibonacci Sequence (A058981) occur.

A058984.name: Number of partitions of n in which number of parts is not 2.
formula: a(n) = p(n) - floor(n/2), where p(n) = number of partitions of n = A000041(n).

A058986.name: Sorting by prefix reversal (or "flipping pancakes"). You can only reverse segments that include the initial term of the current permutation; a(n) is the number of reversals that are needed to transform an arbitrary permutation of n letters to the identity permutation.
formula: It is known that a(n) >= n+1 for n >= 6, a(n) >= 17*n/16 if n is a multiple of 16 (so a(32) >= 34) and a(n) <= (5*n+5)/3.

There is an improved asymptotic upper bound of (18/11)*n + O(1) for the number of prefix reversals to sort permutations of length n given in the Chitturi et al. paper. - Ivan Hal Sudborough (hal_sud(AT)yahoo.com), Jul 02 2008

A058988.name: For a rational number p/q let f(p/q) = p*q divided by number of divisors of p+q; a(n) is obtained by iterating f, starting at n/1, until an integer is reached, or if no integer is ever reached then a(n) = 0.

A058989.name: Largest number of consecutive integers such that each is divisible by a prime <= the n-th prime.
formula: a(n) = A048670(n) - 1. See that entry for additional information.
Iwaniec proved that a(n) << n^2*(log n)^2. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Sep 08 2012
a(n) >= (2e^gamma + o(1)) n log^2 n log log log n / (log log n)^2, see A048670. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Sep 08 2012
See A048669 for many other bounds and references. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Apr 19 2017

A058990.name: Smallest power of two whose reversal of its n-th power is a prime.

A058991.name: Smallest number not a power of two whose reversal of its n-th power is a prime.

A058992.name: Gossip Problem: there are n people and each of them knows some item of gossip not known to the others. They communicate by telephone and whenever one person calls another, they tell each other all that they know at that time. How many calls are required before each gossip knows everything?

A058993.name: Numbers n such that 5^n reversed is a prime.

A058994.name: Numbers n such that 7^n reversed is prime.

A058995.name: Numbers n such that 13^n reversed is prime.

A058996.name: Primes whose reversal is a fourth power.

A058997.name: Least power k greater than 1 for which n^k reversed is a prime, or 0 if impossible.

A058998.name: Least exponent k for which n^k reversed (leading zeros are not allowed) is a prime, or 0 if impossible.
formula: a(n*10^k) = 0 for all k > 0 since definition does not allow leading 0's.

A058999.name: Primes p such that x^17 = 2 has no solution mod p.

A059000.name: Primes whose reversal is a fifth power.
